DIGITAL GALLERY X CHEIKH PROCTOR1/11/2022

About 


Cheikh Proctor is a 26 year old instrumentalist and emerging graphic artist!. Who always loved strange

and bizarre creations, most of which started with music. They are a drummer and an electronic

musician and through that scope their exposure to the creative flow pushed it’s way

through to visual art. Electronic and experimental works through sound almost pair with visual

works like certain wines and cheeses, in a sense it almost makes it three dimensional and takes

you into a further understanding of what is going on. They were introduced and sort of guided by their

amazing friend and artist Isaak Hoffman or Please_Remove_your_shoes which introduced them to

TouchDesigner which was easy enough to get a grasp around and just explore.


Photo Bio


Most of these in this series revolve around introductory experimentation with archived images

and different themes such as depression, the human experience, perception alterations and

science. They'd like to tighten the weave between science and art which they find to be personally

refreshing. Most of the pics in the series also hold relevance to feelings or moods not

expressible through verbal mediums.

DIGITAL GALLERY X CALLA4/7/2022

Calla is an artist based in Montréal/Tiohti:áke focusing on drawing and painting. They studied art at the Cooper Union for the Advancement of Science and Art. They are interested in creating images that break visual surface and blend boundaries between figure, text, and object through the use of faulty lenses, low exposure/color encoding, and multi-foci. Their work is influenced by the ideas of expanded material empathy and symbolic perspective.

Their project for n.10.as "Images for Listening" explores models for visualizing music. Each image samples a different method, from notation to acoustical modeling to the first video-music synthesizer. See titles for more information on each image.This project is related to past installation works where they collected different forms of produced imagery and constructed them into systems in order to reveal the mechanics of image making and allow multiple perspectives to coexist. The forms of produced imagery that influenced them include informational graphics, scientific notations, and low-fidelity visualizations.

Titles:

1. Atari video music synthesizer

2. Chance operations score after cage

3. Chladni plate for violin

4. Diffusion of sound waves in conversation

5. Music in the brain

6. Nightclub simulator

7. Player piano score

8. That feeling when you are listening and start imagining


You can find them on instagram  @calla1000 or on their website callamcinnes.com

Digital Gallery X Evelina7/11/2021

Evelina Groll is an artist currently residing in Vancouver, BC. Mostly dealing with topics around sense of place, traditions, and human/nature interactions, she works in photography and textiles, and is currently a filmmaking student at SFU.

This photo series is a collected series of images taken in the past year and a half that explores the way we perceive nature. The very nature of the word "nature" implies that humans are separate from it, when truly everything on the planet is so interwoven that nothing can be fully isolated - not the animal kingdoms, not political topics, not human and "other". Never showing the full picture, these photos attempt to isolate parts of nature and in doing so show that that is impossible.

DIGITAL GALLERY X KAYLA TAYLOR1/6/2021

Kayla Taylor is an artist based in Chicago. They are work in many mediums and draw inspiration from environments. More recently the work has been exploring new, imagined landscapes, unsettling scenes, and bodily shapes. They want these worlds to feel like something unknown, somewhere to find new thoughts. 

These digital worlds came out of an initial fascination with swamps, marshes, and wetland meadows. They were doing a lot of research into these environments and have been captivated by the way watery landscapes process life cycles faster. More life collects here because of the water, the plants, the movement, and because of this there are more deaths, decomposition, intricacy, and then nutrients for even more life. When you are in a place like this you can almost feel the life transferring from above ground to below, then around, between, and back up again.

Patient O is a collection of poems, stories, and artworks characterized by early quarantine-horniness and depression that coalesced into a vision of coronavirus-themed erotica. Patient O seeks to work through all these feelings: desire, frustration, longing, rage, disappointment, and, of course, lust. Digital Gallery x Sarita26/9/2020

After studying theoretical and applied art at Stockholm University, La Sorbonne in Paris as well as at UNAM in Mexico City, Sarita developed an approach centered on the aesthetic manifestations of nature by moving in 2018 to Sörmland, a forested region of Sweden. Birch in all its uniqueness and versatility gradually becomes the starting point of any project both sculptural and two-dimensional. She exhibits her works in Europe and North America.

These eight backgrounds featured on n10.as are geometrical compositions highlighting the large variety of birch bark tones and creating unique tapestries. Sarita's large-scale sustainable wall-hangings celebrate the design qualities of the Betula Papyrifera (paper birch). This species of birch, only to be found in North America, have many layers of skin peeling off in a wide range of shades. With the lenticel’s stripe-patterns enhancing the interwoven aspect, the thinness of paper and softness of fabric, makes it the perfect medium for revisited textile art.

Discover more of Sarita's work:IG: @sarita.arte

BACKGROUNDS BY Gabriel Guzmán13/4/2020

Gabriel Guzmán (Human) is a Mexican artist highly influenced by graphics and aesthetics related to the surreal and science fiction. He is mainly interested in humans and their relationship with natural and artificial environments, and how they shape us and create social behaviors that define us as agents of change, assimilation and mutation. 

Currently based in Mexico City, he works on different projects involving the mural, painting, digital illustration and design as his main tools, while in a continuous search to expand the techniques he uses.


These eight background images stem from ideas previously conceived which could not be adequately concluded. Performed as exercises to create characters, atmospheres or environments, each one is delimited by certain themes and colors exclusively for this n10.as digital residency where he could play with greater expressiveness. He states, "[I was] thinking that visualization was optimal and tried to create harmony between the visuals and the music that I have been able to hear on this platform."

Monthly e-station make-over thanks to artist Christopher Burrows gracing us with eight new groovy backgrounds!


Christopher Burrows - born in 1992 in Perth, Australia. Running his multidisciplinary freelance studio from Kruezberg, Berlin, he works in illustration, graphic art & design, and 2D animation. DIGITAL GALLERY X SERIOUS COMPUTER GROUP18/12/2019

Serious Computer Group (SCG) is the duo of Nina Bouchard and Evan Montpellier. Founded in 2018 and based in Montreal, SCG works across a range of physical and digital disciplines, including interactive installation, photography and filmmaking, programming and electronics, sound and video art. SCG's goal is to synthesize its diverse practices into novel hybrid aesthetic languages, balancing formal experimentation with an accessible sensibility and an appreciation for narrative. 


https://serious.computer  |  https://evanmontpellier.net  |  http://ninabouchard.com 


The background images are derived from Phase, a responsive video installation. Phase is a study of water, combining video footage and synthesized graphics to generate evolving visual patterns. The work was installed at the FOFA Gallery in the EV Building at Concordia University, 1515 St-Catherine St. West, Montreal from Nov. 4 to Dec. 13, 2019. 


If you’re interested in doing a digital residency, email gallery@n10.as :)

DIGITAL GALLERY X MATISSE A-M 16/7/2019

Delve into the colourful world of artist Matisse A-M, taking over our homepage this month. Newfangled backgrounds, sidebar icons, and N10.AS logo :-) 


Matisse A-M is going for a quick dive in the pool in search of tiny strange sneaky worlds (full of everything) that go eee(h)e(h)e/ooo(p).


This is how it happened: the creaturehangout was found on a thick ledge on a reaaallly beige street. I almostalready put them in my pocket-- but didn’t know if these were lost creatures on a wander or if they had just been pushed aside. So, aroundandaround (at least 3-7 times with breaks), up and down the chairs, againandagain, even a nap (that was really just staring at the ceiling) until never-being-able-to-really-know and the possibility of them missing to the wrong place took over and so I had to sneak to get them. hehe, they splashed into a metal stirring bowl (that had no flat part on the bottom so it kept spilling oops) and now they get carried around (in pockets)!!

Digital Gallery x John Hanchar 17/6/2019

Homepage summer make-over by artist John Hanchar! Peep the eight backgrounds and new logo he created as an invitation to reflect on the history & future of radio communication. 


John Hanchar is a Newfoundlander who found himself living in Montréal for a few years before leaving this past April to teach overseas. He’s currently based in Yangzhou, Jiangsu Province, PRC. Relatively new to digital art, he became interested in it by helping to design show posters while living/volunteering with the La Plante collective. His work seeks to examine the aesthetic power of images in tandem with their historical connotation. 

"This collection of digital collages (all of which were created using GIMP specifically for the n10.as digital residency) was inspired by a series of topics spanning a historical period of nearly 90 years, touching on the different ways radio has existed as a platform - both ideologically and physically. In blending the meanings of the “platform” and situating n10.as both in our real history (while allowing room to play with other potential realities) it is designed to start a conversation about the history of broadcast media and corporate ownership of the airwaves. Context clues have been left with the intention of giving  the viewer a chance to pursue the references at their own leisure, should they so wish."


To discover more of John's work: @vir69o on Instagram

Digital Gallery x Rebecca Ladds14/5/2019

Our homepage has been graced by a new web take-over - courtesy of the talented Rebecca Ladds, an artist currently living in Montreal, QC.


Feast your eyes on the fresh new icons (left sidebar) + eight backgrounds (top right corner) she created by toggling through 'em. Seep deeper into her bewitching world by following @rebeccaladds & visiting rebeccaladds.com


While analogue drawing rests as the foundation of her practice, she has recently been experimenting with digital collage using elements from her drawings, animations, videos and photos to create fictional environments.


For n10.as, she imagines the website as a clear window pane where visitors can gaze out into other worlds. Within which, the inhabitants (mostly horses, sometimes fish), are liberated from expectation and analysis; they are free to reside in their own utopian habitats. Seems nice!

Hors Circuit Broadcast26/8/2018

This is a statement in regards to n10.as' decision to withdraw from the "Hors Circuit" event being held at Le Virage on August 26th, presented by Red Bull Music and MUTEK. We agreed to live stream this event as apart of our partnership agreement with MUTEK, but we feel it is necessary to withdraw following concerns raised by hosts and members of our station regarding the gentrifying effects of events like this on Parc-Extension, the neighbourhood on which Le Virage borders. 


These hosts are members of the organizations Parc-Ex Hutchison Group, Parc-Ex contre la gentrification, Parc-Ex Action Squad, and AASK Montreal. These organizations dedicate their time and resources against the gentrification of Parc-Extension and we would like to acknowledge and support these efforts. n10.as exists thanks to the contributions of our hosts and communities, we believe it is our responsibility to act in a way that respects their concerns and to amplify their voices.
